org.tms.api

Interface Table

  • All Superinterfaces:
    BaseElement, IndexableTableElements, InitializableTableProperties, Listenable, TableElement, Taggable

    public interface Table
extends TableElement, InitializableTableProperties
    A standard two dimensional table consisting of Rows, Columns, and Cells, and, optionally, Subsets. Tables are the key element in the TMS subsystem and only through table instance objects is it possible to create rows, columns, cells, and subsets.

    The Table interface defines the methods available to operate on tables, including adding and retrieving Rows, Columns, Cells, and Subsets, to get and set cell values, and to perform table-wide operations, such as sorting, recalculating derived elements, and manipulating the current cell. It also defines methods to get and set table-wide properties such as row and column allocation increments, and to manage thread pool characteristics for the thread pools available to execute asynchronous derivations and to service event listeners. Thread pool management is an optional feature that not all table implementations may support. See TableContext for more information on these capabilities.

    TMS Tables are similar to Microsoft Excel spreadsheets in that both:

    • are cell-oriented,
    • have rows, columns, and multiple sheets,
    • allow table cells to contain data of different types (e.g., A1 is a number, B1 is a String), as well as contain the result of a calculation (known as a Derivation in TMS),
    • automatically recalculate derivations when the data (table cells) on which they depend change,
    • allow rows, columns, and cell ranges to be grouped into Subsets,
    • support formatting,
    • are sortable.

    TMS Tables differ from standard spreadsheets and provide the following advantages:

    • cells can contain any valid Java class instance, including those defined by the JDK (String, Integer, etc.), as well as custom classes your application provides,
    • derivations (formulas) can be assigned to columns and rows, as well as to specific cells; whenever cells are modified that affect the column (row) derivation, the appropriate cells in the column (row) are recalculated as well,
    • new functions can be registered (see Operator) that can be used in Column, Row, and Cell Derivations to operate on standard Java data types as well as custom data types,
    • functions can execute asynchronously and post results to the table when complete; cells dependent on asynchronous calculations are put into a pending state,
    • derivations referring to pending cells will suspend until they are able to proceed (all pending cells are resolved),
    • Rows and columns can be named, in addition to cells and subsets (cell ranges),
    • the numeric precision (number of significant digits) used to express derivation results can be specified,
    • custom Java Comparators can be supplied to sort rows and columns,
    • cells can be constrained to specific data-types,
    • cell validators (and transformers) can be defined to help enforce data integrity,
    • event listeners are supported and can be registered on tables, rows, columns, and cells.

    • Method Detail

      • addRow

        Row addRow()
        Add a new Row to this Table directly following the current row. If the current row is last, the new Row is added to the end of the table. Otherwise, the new Row is inserted directly following the current row, and all other rows are moved down by one.
        Returns:
        the new Row
        Throws:
        DeletedElementException - if this table has been deleted

      • addRow

        Row addRow(int idx)
        Add a new Row to this Table at the 1-based index specified by idx. If the idx value is greater than the number of rows currently in the table, additional new rows are added, and the table will contain idx rows when the operation completes. Otherwise, the new Row is inserted at the position specified by idx and all existing rows are moved down by one.
        Parameters:
        idx - the 1-based index where the new row will be inserted or added
        Returns:
        the new Row
        Throws:
        InvalidAccessException - if idx is <= 0
        DeletedElementException - if this table has been deleted

      • addRow

        Row addRow(Access mode,
           Object... mda)
        Add a new Row to this Table using the Access specified by mode and the optional argument(s) specified in mda. See the Javadoc on Access to learn more about the various Access modes and their required parameters (if any).

        If the new Row is added at a position greater than the current number of rows in the table, additional new rows are added, as needed. Otherwise, the new Row is inserted at the position specified by mda and all existing rows are moved down by one.

        Parameters:
        mode - the Access mode to use to add the row
        mda - the additional parameters required by the specified Access mode
        Returns:
        the new Row
        Throws:
        InvalidAccessException - if an invalid mode and/or mda is specified
        DeletedElementException - if this table has been deleted

      • sort

        void sort(ElementType et,
          TableProperty tp,
          TableRowColumnElement... others)
        Sorts this Table by a TableProperty, such as TableProperty.Label and then by the table elements specified by others. If et is ElementType.Row, then the TableRowColumnElement elements specified in others must all be Columns. Similarly, if et is ElementType.Column, then the TableRowColumnElement must all be Rows.
        Parameters:
        et - the ElementType to sort in this table (Row or Column)
        tp - the optional TableProperty to use as the initial sort criterium
        others - the additional Rows or Columns to use as sort criteria
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if et is null or if tp and others are null
        NullPointerException - if an element in others is null
        InvalidParentException - if an element in others isn't associated with this Table
        InvalidException - if et is not ElementType.Row or ElementType#Column
        DeletedElementException - if this table has been deleted

      • delete

        void delete(TableElement... elements)
        Deletes the table elements in this Table specified in elements. Deleted elements are removed from any containing Subsets, and any Derivations that reference a deleted element are also removed.
        Parameters:
        elements - the table elements to delete
